## Membership Issues and Legitimacy Problems

The League’s membership composition and its association with the Treaty of Versailles contributed to its lack of credibility.

### Perception as an Instrument of the Victors

The League was closely tied to the Treaty of Versailles, which was perceived as a punitive peace imposed by the victors on the defeated powers, especially Germany. This association led many to view the League as an instrument of the victorious Allied powers rather than a neutral peacekeeping body ([Gk Scientist, 2021](https://gkscientist.com/causes-of-the-failure-of-the-league-of-nations/); [StudyMode, n.d.](https://www.studymode.com/essays/Explain-Why-The-League-Of-Nations-69256270.html)).

### Economic and Military Weakness of Member States

Many European countries were economically weakened and militarily depleted after World War I. They were more focused on national reconstruction than on international cooperation. This lack of enthusiasm and capacity undermined the League’s effectiveness ([StudyMode, n.d.](https://www.studymode.com/essays/Explain-Why-The-League-Of-Nations-69256270.html)).

---

## External Factors and Changing Global Context

The League’s failure was also influenced by broader geopolitical and economic factors beyond its control.

### The Great Depression

The global economic crisis of the 1930s diverted attention and resources away from international cooperation. Economic nationalism and protectionism increased, reducing the willingness of states to cooperate through the League ([GraduateWay, n.d.](https://graduateway.com/why-did-the-league-of-nations-fail/)).

### Rise of Totalitarian Regimes

The rise of aggressive totalitarian regimes in Germany, Italy, and Japan, whose peoples supported imperialistic policies, directly challenged the League’s principles. These regimes pursued expansionist policies that the League was unable to check effectively ([Gk Scientist, 2021](https://gkscientist.com/causes-of-the-failure-of-the-league-of-nations/)).

