## Conclusion and Opinion

The failure of the League of Nations was not due to a single flaw but rather a complex interplay of structural, political, and contextual factors. Structurally, the League was handicapped by its reliance on unanimous decisions and lack of enforcement power. Politically, the absence of key powers like the United States and the self-interested behavior of dominant members like Britain and France critically undermined its authority. The League’s association with the Treaty of Versailles and its perception as a victor’s club further eroded its legitimacy. Finally, external factors such as the Great Depression and the rise of aggressive totalitarian regimes overwhelmed the League’s idealistic framework.

In my reasoned opinion, the League’s failure was ultimately rooted in its foundational contradiction: it was an international organization committed to collective security and peace but was built upon the principle of state sovereignty and voluntary cooperation. Without the genuine commitment of its most powerful members and an effective enforcement mechanism, the League was doomed to fail. It was a pioneering experiment that laid important groundwork but lacked the practical tools and political will necessary to maintain peace in a turbulent interwar world.

